M|references|Words, phrases, and punctuation patterns commonly associated with AI-generated text. Avoid these to ensure writing sounds natural and human.
M|references|Sources: Grammarly (2025), Microsoft 365 Life Hacks (2025), GPTHuman (2025), Walter Writes (2025), Textero (2025), Plagiarism Today (2025), Rolling Stone (2025), MDPI Blog (2025)
M|references|- Em Dashes: The Primary AI Tell
M|references|- Overused Verbs
M|references|- Overused Adjectives
M|references|- Overused Transitions and Connectors
M|references|- Phrases That Signal AI Writing (Opening Phrases, Transitional Phrases, Concluding Phrases, Structural Patterns)
M|references|- Filler Words and Empty Intensifiers
M|references|- Academic-Specific AI Tells
M|references|- How to Self-Check
M|references|**The em dash (—) has become one of the most reliable markers of AI-generated cnt.**
M|references|Em dashes are longer than hyphens (-) and are used for emphasis, interruptions, or parenthetical information. While they have legitimate uses in writing, AI models drastically overuse them.
M|references|- AI models were trained on edited books, academic papers, and style guides where em dashes appear frequently
M|references|- AI uses em dashes as a shortcut for sentence variety instead of commas, colons, or parentheses
M|references|- Most human writers rarely use em dashes because they don't exist as a standard keyboard key
M|references|- The overuse is so consistent that it has become the unofficial signature of ChatGPT writing
M|references|| Instead of | Use |
M|references||------------|-----|
M|references|| The results—which were surprising—showed... | The results, which were surprising, showed... |
M|references|| This approach—unlike traditional methods—allows... | This approach, unlike traditional methods, allows... |
M|references|| The study found—as expected—that... | The study found, as expected, that... |
M|references|| Communication skills—both written and verbal—are essential | Communication skills (both written and verbal) are essential |
M|references|- Use commas for most parenthetical information
M|references|- Use colons to introduce explanations or lists
M|references|- Use parentheses for supplementary information
M|references|- Reserve em dashes for rare, deliberate emphasis only
M|references|- If you find yourself using more than one em dash per page, revise
